INSERT INTO "analytics" ("id","shortcode","target_url","ip_address","user_agent","referrer","screen_width","screen_height","language","country","city","region","latitude","longitude","postal_code","timezone","timestamp") VALUES(268,'ghj1je',replace('Sir,\nOn Friday, October 2nd, 2025, at approximately 0945 hours, I received a radio call for an arrest attempt at the Missouri Department of Corrections, Division of Probation and Parole – St. Louis District Office, 10805 Sunset Office Drive, Suite 200, St. Louis, MO 63127.\n\nUpon arrival, I contacted Probation and Parole Officers Jennifer Lynn Whitaker (PPO-4512) and Thomas Edward Reyes (PPO-3289), both of whom provided documentation verifying the identity and active bench warrant for the subject to be arrested. The office was a standard probation meeting room containing a table and two chairs, occupied by Harlan and Probation Officer Whitaker. The atmosphere was calm and controlled prior to contact.\n\nI was wearing a full Olivette Police Department duty uniform and operating fully marked patrol vehicle PV133. Officer Parks (DSN 1920) arrived in full duty uniform operating fully marked patrol vehicle PV120.\n\nSuspect Information:\nHarlan, Robert James\nW/M, DOB: 08/12/1985\nHeight: 6’01”, Weight: 220 lbs\nHair: Brown, Eyes: Blue\nHome Address: 456 Elm Street, St. Louis, MO 63103\nPhone: 314-555-2384\nWarrant: Failure to Appear (Bench Warrant issued 07/15/2025) – Class D Felony Stealing ($1,200 merchandise value).\n\nHarlan was seated in a chair in a probation office room when I identified myself as an Olivette Police Officer. Harlan appeared sober, alert, and not under the influence of alcohol or narcotics. He displayed clear speech but was verbally agitated and argumentative. I informed him that he was under arrest for violating the terms of his probation and failing to appear in court.\n\nHarlan refused to comply with verbal commands to stand, stating, “I ain’t under arrest, I didn’t do nothing wrong.” I repeated my lawful command for him to stand and comply, warning that if he did not, he would be physically assisted to his feet. Harlan again refused. Verbal de-escalation was attempted several times, including calm explanations of the situation and repeated lawful commands before any physical contact occurred.\n\nMyself and my partner, Officer Parks (DSN 1920), each took hold of Harlan’s arms, grasping his forearm and bicep to elevate him from his seated position. Harlan retracted both arms and began yelling that he was not under arrest. We lifted him from the chair by his arms and guided him away from the table to prevent obstruction.\n\nOnce standing, Harlan attempted to pull away from our grasp. At this point, Officer Parks dropped to a knee and secured Harlan’s legs while I maintained control of his upper body, pulling him forward to off-balance him. Harlan was taken to the ground in a controlled manner.\n\nWhile on the ground, I secured Harlan’s left wrist in a handcuff while stating, “You are under arrest, stop resisting.” I then ordered him to place his right hand in the small of his back. He refused multiple times, at which point I reached under him, grasped his right wrist, and guided it behind his back to apply the second cuff. Both cuffs were checked for proper fit and double-locked.\n\nOnce restrained, Harlan calmed down and ceased resistance. I informed him that he was under arrest and asked, “Do you have anything on your person that could hurt me or yourself before I search you?” Harlan replied, “No.”\n\nI conducted a search of Harlan, beginning with the waistband and moving through the front pockets, legs, and torso area. No weapons, contraband, or illegal items were found.\n\nMy partner and I assisted Harlan to his feet and escorted him to my marked patrol vehicle. During this time, I asked Harlan if he was injured or needed medical attention, to which he responded that he “ain’t a bitch” and didn’t need “no fucking help.” He was transported to the St. Louis County Jail – Booking without incident. The transport lasted approximately 15 minutes. During transport, Harlan was calm, compliant, and cooperative.\n\nNo injuries were reported by Harlan or any officers involved. The incident was witnessed by PPO Whitaker and PPO Reyes, both of whom confirmed that minimal force was used and that Harlan’s resistance was limited to verbal refusal, body tensing, and retraction from our grasp. The use of force lasted less than 45 seconds.\n\nUpon arrival at the jail, Harlan was booked in reference to his warrant for Failure to Appear. Sergeant Hale (DSN 1234) was notified of the incident and reviewed the use of force. Sergeant Hale also interviewed PPO Whitaker and PPO Reyes, who confirmed that Harlan’s resistance consisted of verbal noncompliance and physical tensing.\n\nAdditional information and supplements will follow in the usual manner.\n\nRespectfully,\nRecruit Weckmann DSN 275','\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2025-11-05T13:05:10.264Z');
